{
  "text": "Blocking DNA repair is an attractive strategy for sensitizing cancer cells to radio-and/or chemotherapy, and being at the initiating point of the DNA repair cascades, PARP1 is a valid target for these strategies. Several PARP-specific inhibitors have been developed up to date; including niraparib (MK-4827), olaparib (AZD-2281) and veliparib (ABT-888) which are currently tested in clinical studies. These inhibitors are especially potent when applied to breast cancer gene (BRCA) deficient cells, in which they induce synthetic cytotoxicity [CITATION_1] . However, the results of the clinical studies are so far contradictory. Furthermore, the molecular mechanisms of action of the PARP-targeting compounds (e.g. catalytic inhibition, or additional PARP1-\"trapping\") require additional investigation.",
